Part 1 : Introduction ¶

Motivation¶

In the early 2020, we encountered something most of us had never thought of experiencing in our lifetime: A global pandemic.

In March 2020, I remember being in a classroom in high school as a senior, hearing the announcement and being happy to go home early, not knowing what was about to happen next. Most teachers and students had expected to be back in school within a couple weeks, which turned out to be wrong. Although the virus started in late 2019, most people did not know or care about it until the lockdown started. In the state of Maryland, Governor Hogan ordered a lockdown on March 23rd, 2020 and it lasted until June 15th, 2021. Now, we're in 2022 but I'm quite certain that we all agree on how much impact this virus has had in people's lives across the globe.
Therefore, for my final project of the intro data science course, I want to explore the factors that can affect the mortaility rate of covid and create a model that predicts the mortality rate of a covid patients based on their health conditions.

Clarification of the Columns in the Dataset¶

  • USMER : whether the patient treated medical units of the first, second or third level; 1, 2, 3, respectively.
  • medical unit : the medical unit where the patient was treated.
  • sex : 1 for female and 2 for male.
  • patient type : 1 for patients that returned home, 2 for those who were hospitalized
  • date_died : date of death; 9999-99-99 for patients who are still alive.
  • copd : whether the patient has chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
  • inmsupr : whether the patient has immunosuppression.
  • other disease : whether the patient has other diseases.
  • classification_final : covid test results; 1-3 for positive, 4-7 for negative or inconclusive.


For the boolean values, 1 means yes, 2 means no, and 97/99 means unknown.

Part 3 : Data Management/Processing ¶

Looking at the columns, we can see that there are a few columns that are not necessary for our analysis. Therefore, I will drop those columns.
First, I will drop USMER and MEDICAL UNIT because they're related to the medical unit where the patient was treated and that information isn't super relevant for our analysis of the mortality rate based on health conditions.
In addition, I will drop OTHER_DISEASE because it's not clear what other diseases the patients have so it's not very useful. Also, I will drop CLASSIFICATION_FINAL (covid test results) since everyone in the dataset is a covid patient, which makes this column not all that relevant.
Lastly, I will drop PATIENT_TYPE, INTUBED and ICU because I want to focus on health conditions that affect the mortality rate of covid patients. Those three columns are related to the treatment of the patients and not their health conditions so we will drop them.

Additionally, I see some typos in the column names, so I will fix those as well.

To make things less confusing, I will modify the boolean values in other columns to follow the standard of the values 0 being false and 1 being true, instead of 2 being false and 1 being true.

Also, for the DATE_DIED column, what we're interested in is whether the patient died or not, so I will change the values to 0 for alive and 1 for dead as well as change the column name to DEATH.

In [189]:
# replace the values of 1 with 0 and 2 with 1 to make things more intuitive

# columns with boolean values are:
bool_columns = ["SEX", "PNEUMONIA", "PREGNANT", "DIABETES", \
    "COPD", "ASTHMA", "IMMSUPR", "HYPERTENSION", "CARDIOVASCULAR", "OBESITY", \
    "RENAL_CHRONIC", "TOBACCO"]

# replacing the values
for column in bool_columns:
    df[column] = df[column].apply(lambda x : 1 if x == 2 else (0 if x == 1 else x))
    
# replacing the values in DATE_DIED column and renaming the column
df['DATE_DIED'] = df['DATE_DIED'].apply(lambda x : 0 if x == "9999-99-99" else 1)
df.rename(columns={'DATE_DIED':'DEATH'}, inplace=True)

While trying to drop missing values, I noticed that dropping the missing values in the PREGNANT column was leaving only the value of 0 in the SEX column. Upon some investigation, I realized that it's because for men, the PREGNANT column value is always 97. Since the missing value for women is always 98, we can safely change all 97's to 0's. Therefore, I will change this value to 0 to avoid this affecting our analysis. Then, I will drop the missing values.

for column in columns:

By looking at the plot, it seems that other than pneumonia, most health conditions show similar mortality rates. However, from the heapmap above, we saw that age, pneumonia, diabetes, and hypertension are among the most correlated variables with mortality rates. Therefore, it's hard to conclude that penumonia is not a factor affecting the mortality rate of covid patients severely. Therefore, I will go with the 4 variables obtained from the heapmap and analyze them further. Specifically, I want to test all possible combinations of the highly correlated variables and look at the mortality rate of each. Ideally, I'd want to test all combinations that can be obtained by combining the 11 health condition variables, but that'd yield 11! combinations, which is of course too many. Therefore, I will go with the 4 variables that are the most correlated with the target variable.

In [200]:
var_list = ['PNEUMONIA', 'DIABETES', 'HYPERTENSION'] # list of variables to combine

def combinations(var_list):
    list = []
    for L in range(2, len(var_list) + 1):
        list.extend(itertools.combinations(var_list, L))
    return list

comb_list = combinations(var_list) # list of combinations

fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=2)
row, col = 0, 0 # index values for the grid

# loop through each combination and create a bar plot
for comb in comb_list:
    df_cond = df.copy()
    for i in range(len(comb)):
        df_cond = df_cond[df_cond[comb[i]] == 1]
    
    death_cond = []
    for age_group in age_groups:
        df_age = df_cond[df_cond['AGE_GROUP'] == age_group]
        death_cond.append(len(df_age[df_age['DEATH'] == 1].index) / len(df_age.index))

    # bar plot
    ax = sns.barplot(x=age_groups, y=death_cond, ax=axs[row][col])
    ax.set_title(f"Mortality Rate vs. {comb}")
    ax.set_xlabel("Age Group")
    ax.set_ylabel("Mortality Rate")

    # setting index values for the grid
    if col == 1:
        row += 1
        col = 0
    else:
        col += 1
        
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We can see that the mortality rates differ, but again, since age is the largest factor affecting the mortality rate, it's hard to compare the mortality rates between the combinations. Therefore, I will create a plot comparing the mortality rates between the combinations for each of the age groups. Part 5 : Hypothesis Testing ¶

Hypothesis : The health condition variables are not correlated with the moratlity rate of covid patients.

To test this hypothesis, I will use Pearson's correlation coefficient. The null hypothesis is that the correlation coefficient is 0, which means that there is no correlation between the variables. The alternative hypothesis is that the correlation coefficient is not 0, which means that there is a correlation between the variables.

In [202]:
for col in cols:
    corr, p = pearsonr(df[col], df['DEATH'])

    if p < 0.05:
        print(f"{col} - Correlation: {corr}, p-value: {p}")

PREGNANT - Correlation: -0.07685065808419557, p-value: 0.0
OBESITY - Correlation: -0.05651224850606834, p-value: 0.0
TOBACCO - Correlation: -0.005199646460595949, p-value: 1.4343233753842935e-07
PNEUMONIA - Correlation: -0.47081483420141984, p-value: 0.0
DIABETES - Correlation: -0.2171971270179021, p-value: 0.0
COPD - Correlation: -0.08988532365020493, p-value: 0.0
ASTHMA - Correlation: 0.01734857124446184, p-value: 5.56286939801154e-69
IMMSUPR - Correlation: -0.04930898750020367, p-value: 0.0
HYPERTENSION - Correlation: -0.2052520944882401, p-value: 0.0
CARDIOVASCULAR - Correlation: -0.07681276484639363, p-value: 0.0
RENAL_CHRONIC - Correlation: -0.11946382716657909, p-value: 0.0

Because all of the p-values are less than 0.05, the correlations are statistically significant. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a correlation between each of the health condition variables and the mortality rate of covid patients.

Part 6 : Training the Machine Learning Model ¶

For the machine learning model that predicts the mortality of covid patients, I will be using two different algorithms: Logistic Regression and Random Forest. I will be using the accuracy, precision and recall metrics to evaluate the performance of the models. I will also be using 10-fold-cross-validation to evaluate the performance of the models.

Logistic Regression¶

In [203]:
# dropping age group as it's not needed anymore
df.drop(columns=['AGE_GROUP'], inplace=True)

X = df.iloc[:,1:] # select all columns but the first one
y = df.iloc[:,0] # select just the first column (target)
 
# scale the age column
mm_scaler = MinMaxScaler()
X = pd.DataFrame(mm_scaler.fit_transform(X))

# dropping na values and running Logistic Regression
df.dropna(inplace=True)
log = LogisticRegression()
log.fit(X, y)

# 10-fold cross validation for accuracy, precision, and recall
ten_fold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
acc_scores = cross_val_score(log, X, y, scoring='accuracy', cv=ten_fold)
pre_scores = cross_val_score(log, X, y, scoring='precision', cv=ten_fold)
rec_scores = cross_val_score(log, X, y, scoring='recall', cv=ten_fold)
print(f"Accuracy: {mean(acc_scores)}")
print(f"Precision: {mean(pre_scores)}")
print(f"Recall: {mean(rec_scores)}")

Accuracy: 0.9326663073407501
Precision: 0.5685284504762107
Recall: 0.33227884886401965

We can see that the accuracy is very high but precision and recall are extremely low. This is probably because the dataset is imbalanced. Let's count the number of 0's and 1's in the target variable.

In [204]:
# counting the number of deaths and alive
print(f"Dead : {len(df[df['DEATH'] == 1].index)}")
print(f"Alive : {len(df[df['DEATH'] == 0].index)}")

Dead : 74925
Alive : 948723

As expected, there are way more 0's than 1's, which is causing the problem. Initially, I tried using oversampling method but since it was taking too long, I will try the undersampling method to resample the data.

In [205]:
# undersampling the majority class
under = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy=0.5)
X, y = under.fit_resample(X, y)

# logistic regression and 10-fold cross validation
log = LogisticRegression()
log.fit(X, y)

acc_scores = cross_val_score(log, X, y, scoring='accuracy', cv=ten_fold)
pre_scores = cross_val_score(log, X, y, scoring='precision', cv=ten_fold)
rec_scores = cross_val_score(log, X, y, scoring='recall', cv=ten_fold)
print(f"Accuracy: {mean(acc_scores)}")
print(f"Precision: {mean(pre_scores)}")
print(f"Recall: {mean(rec_scores)}")

Accuracy: 0.8565988428431887
Precision: 0.8090877115080632
Recall: 0.7457622529366641

Random Forest¶

After undersampling, the performance of the model has improved significantly. However, just to see if a different algorithm performs better, I will try using random forest algorithm this time to see if it achieves better results.

First, I will use grid search to tune the hyperparameters of the model.

In [206]:
# undersampling
under = RandomUnderSampler(sampling_strategy=0.5)
X_res, y_res = under.fit_resample(X, y)

# grid search to find out the best hyperparameters
max_depth = [2, 8, 16]
n_estimators = [64, 128, 256]
param_grid = dict(max_depth=max_depth, n_estimators=n_estimators)

dfrst = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_estimators, max_depth=max_depth)
grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=dfrst, param_grid=param_grid, cv=10)
grid_results = grid.fit(X_res, y_res)

print(f"{grid_results.best_params_}")

{'max_depth': 8, 'n_estimators': 128}
In [207]:
# random forest with the best hyperparameters
forest = RandomForestClassifier(criterion='gini', max_depth=8, n_estimators=128, random_state=1)
fr = forest.fit(X_res, y_res)

# 10-fold cross validation to find out the accuracy, precision, and recall
acc_scores = cross_val_score(fr, X_res, y_res, scoring='accuracy', cv=ten_fold)
pre_scores = cross_val_score(fr, X_res, y_res, scoring='precision', cv=ten_fold)
rec_scores = cross_val_score(fr, X_res, y_res, scoring='recall', cv=ten_fold)
print(f"Accuracy: {mean(acc_scores)}")
print(f"Precision: {mean(pre_scores)}")
print(f"Recall: {mean(rec_scores)}")

Accuracy: 0.8578534034512043
Precision: 0.7951704239395262
Recall: 0.7726069620794511

Using the hyperparameters obtained by grid search, I trained the model and improved the overall performance of the model. The result is similar to that of the logistic regression model after undersampling, but it's still a huge improvement from the original model.

Part 7 : Summary & Conclusion ¶

Summary¶

  • The mortality rate of covid patients is higher for older people.
  • The combination of diabetes and hypertension causes the highest mortality rate among covid patients across all age groups.
  • The health condition variables are highly correlated with the mortality rate of covid patients.
  • It's important to avoid tobacco use and obesity to prevent deaths from covid.
  • The machine learning model that predicts the mortality rate of covid patients achieved an average of 86% accuracy, 80% precision and 77% recall scores.

Conclusion¶

Finally, we went through the entire data science pipeline. My initial interest was figuring out what factors impact the mortality rate of covid patients the most and coming up with a machine learning model that predicts the mortality rate of covid patients based on the health condition variables.
Through the data exploration and analysis, I learned that pre-existing health conditions do affect the mortality rates of covid patients significantly, especially for older people. An interesting finding was that the combination of diabetes and hypertension caused the highest mortality rate among covid patients across all age groups, despite not being the most significant factors when examined individually. Therefore, it's important to take care of your health and get regular checkups to prevent these diseases from developing further.
Another interesting finding was that tobacco use and obesity had just as much impact on the mortality rate as other health conditions, meaning that maintaining a healthy lifestyle is just as important as well. Lastly, I trained a machine learning model that predicts the mortality rate of covid patients and was able to achieve an average of 86% accuracy, 80% precision and 77% recall scores. I hope this project can provide some insights to you and help people stay safe during this pandemic.
